<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910129-0002</DOCNO><DOCID>910129-0002.</DOCID><HL>   Small Pleads Guilty   In Insider-Trading Case   Tied to Business Week</HL><DATE>01/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DNY MHP</CO><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENTS (RGU)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)INDUSTRIAL andamp; COMMERCIAL SERVICES, LEASING, CLEANING (ICS)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A California investor, who was charged withprofiting from advance knowledge of a Business Week magazinecolumn, pleaded guilty in federal court here to two counts ofinsider trading.   The investor, Lawrence Small of Pacific Palisades, Calif.,is the fourth person to plead guilty in the case. Accordingto the suit filed by the government, Mr. Small made profitsof more than $57,000 between September 1986 and July 1988,using the advance information.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Small, who faces a maximum prison sentence of 10 yearsand a fine of as much as $500,000, couldn't be reached forcomment.   The suit charges that Mr. Small received the earlyinformation about what would appear in the magazine's &quot;InsideWall Street&quot; column from Shayne Walters, a former employee ofR.R. Donnelley andamp; Sons Co., printer of Business Week forMcGraw-Hill Inc., the publisher.   The suit charges that Mr. Small paid Mr. Walters to getinformation from the column and deliver it to John Petit, astockbroker at Smith Barney, Harris Upham andamp; Co. in NewportBeach, Calif. Messrs. Petit, Rasinsky and Small would thenpurchase stocks mentioned in the column on Thursdays, beforethe information become public.   The magazine is generally made available to the public onThursdays, after the close of the stock exchange. Stocks thatreceive favorable mention in the column frequently climb inprice after the magazine is released to the public, the suitsaid.   Messrs. Petit and Rasinski have each pleaded guilty to twocounts of insider trading. Mr. Walters has pleaded guilty toconspiracy to commit securities, wire and mail fraud andperjury in the Southern District of New York.</TEXT></DOC>